challengeName: Go Learning Challenge - Learn the basics No.1
detailedRequirements:
Solve the following problem with Golang. The first person to submit a valid solution to satisfy the example cases wins! Topcoder original t-shirts will be given to 3rd - 5th places.

Please submit the following file.

  • glc1.go

The file should include 'main' function that calls your function with the all parameters in the examples and prints results.

Problem Statement

Takumi is the owner of a ski resort in Sapporo City in Japan. The ski resort has N places numbered 0 through N-1. You are given a []int altitude. For each i, the i-th element of altitude is the altitude of the place i.  The skiers would like to follow the path (place 0) -> (place 1) -> ... -> (place N-1). The trip will only be possible if the altitudes of the places are non-increasing. In order to make the trip possible, Takumi now needs to decrease the altitudes of some places. In other words, Takumi wants to decrease some of the altitudes so that altitude[0] >= altitude[1] >= ... >= altitude[N-1] holds. It costs 1 unit of money to decrease the altitude of one place by 1 unit of height.  Return the minimal cost required for the change.

Definition

  • Function : minimumCost
  • Parameters : []int
  • Returns : int
  • Signature : func minimumCost(altitude []int) int

Constraints

  • Altitude will contain between 2 and 50 elements, inclusive
  • Each element of altitude will be between 0 and 1,000, inclusive

Examples

0)

  • {30, 20, 20, 10}
  • Returns: 0

1)

  • {5, 7, 3}
  • Returns: 2
  • Takumi should change the altitude of place 1 (0-based index) from 7 to 5. This changes the sequence of altitudes to {5, 5, 3}. The cost of the change is 7 - 5 = 2 units of money.

2)

  • {6, 8, 5, 4, 7, 4, 2, 3, 1}
  • Returns: 6
  • Takumi should change the altitudes to {6, 6, 5, 4, 4, 4, 2, 2, 1}.

3)

  • {749, 560, 921, 166, 757, 818, 228, 584, 366, 88}
  • Returns: 2284

4)

  • {712, 745, 230, 200, 648, 440, 115, 913, 627, 621, 186, 222, 741, 954, 581, 193, 266, 320, 798, 745}
  • Returns: 6393
